1 Clustering

Clustering is a big topic and hard to do it justice in a single module.

Clustering is an unsupervised learning technique that attempts to group together similar observations. Clustering is commonly applied in Exploratory Data Analysis. Loosely speaking, a clustering algorithm aims to identify groups of observations that are close together (these are the “clusters”), but where there is a clear distinction between individual groups.

1.1 Distance Measures

Although the “normal” Euclidean distance might seem like the obvious choice when calculating the distance between points, it’s not always the best choice. Fortunately we have other options.

1.1.1 Standardising

Before calculating the distance between points it’s important to consider whether or not it’s meaningful to standardise the features. Why? Well, consider the following (somewhat contrived) data, where height is measured in mm and mass is given in 1000 kg.

people
        height     mass
Jimmie    1922 0.107741
Lewis     1758 0.076670
Hollis    1794 0.080466
Jody      1812 0.096476
Timothy   1700 0.082727

The Euclidean distance between these points is completely dominated by the height column. Objectively we see that Jody and Hollis are quite different, yet according to the distance measure they are the most similar pair of points.

dist(people, diag = TRUE)
        Jimmie Lewis Hollis Jody Timothy
Jimmie       0                          
Lewis      164     0                    
Hollis     128    36      0             
Jody       110    54     18    0        
Timothy    222    58     94  112       0

This issue arises because the distance is being calculated from two features with

  1. different units; and
  2. different scales.

In order to make a more sensible distance calculation we need to rectify both of these issues. This can be done by simply standardising each feature.

(people <- scale(people))
           height     mass
Jimmie   1.524993  1.46100
Lewis   -0.479004 -0.93767
Hollis  -0.039102 -0.64462
Jody     0.180849  0.59138
Timothy -1.187735 -0.47008
attr(,"scaled:center")
    height       mass 
1.7972e+03 8.8816e-02 
attr(,"scaled:scale")
   height      mass 
81.836422  0.012954 
dist(people, diag = TRUE)
         Jimmie   Lewis  Hollis    Jody Timothy
Jimmie  0.00000                                
Lewis   3.12564 0.00000                        
Hollis  2.62299 0.52857 0.00000                
Jody    1.60093 1.66535 1.25542 0.00000        
Timothy 3.32986 0.84908 1.16182 1.73197 0.00000

The standardised variables are dimensionless and also have the same mean and variance. Their influence on the distance metric is thus equitable. Let’s take another look.

dist(people, diag = TRUE)
         Jimmie   Lewis  Hollis    Jody Timothy
Jimmie  0.00000                                
Lewis   3.12564 0.00000                        
Hollis  2.62299 0.52857 0.00000                
Jody    1.60093 1.66535 1.25542 0.00000        
Timothy 3.32986 0.84908 1.16182 1.73197 0.00000

With standardised features Lewis and Hollis are the closest points, which ties up with what we observe from the plot above.

Of course, it’s possible that you might want to have a non-uniform contribution to the distance measure, in which case by all means do not standardise your data. However, most often this is a step that you will want to take.

1.1.2 Euclidean Distance

We’ already seen how the Euclidean distance is calculated. Perhaps this is a good opportunity to have a look at some other features of dist(). Firstly, since the diagonal elements are all zero, by default these are not printed.

dist(people)
         Jimmie   Lewis  Hollis    Jody
Lewis   3.12564                        
Hollis  2.62299 0.52857                
Jody    1.60093 1.66535 1.25542        
Timothy 3.32986 0.84908 1.16182 1.73197

You can also choose to include the upper (symmetric) portion of the distance matrix.

dist(people, upper = TRUE)
         Jimmie   Lewis  Hollis    Jody Timothy
Jimmie          3.12564 2.62299 1.60093 3.32986
Lewis   3.12564         0.52857 1.66535 0.84908
Hollis  2.62299 0.52857         1.25542 1.16182
Jody    1.60093 1.66535 1.25542         1.73197
Timothy 3.32986 0.84908 1.16182 1.73197

1.1.3 Manhattan Distance

The Manhattan Distance is also known as the “city block” distance. It’s calculated as the sum of the displacement along each of the coordinate axes (rather than along the diagonal). In two dimensions, this is the sum of the length of the two perpendicular sides of the triangle rather than the hypotenuse.

dist(people, method = "manhattan")
         Jimmie   Lewis  Hollis    Jody
Lewis   4.40267                        
Hollis  3.66972 0.73295                
Jody    2.21377 2.18890 1.45595        
Timothy 4.64382 1.17632 1.32317 2.43004

This might be used, for example, to calculate the shortest distance that a vehicle must travel between two points within a city, since the vehicle is confined to moving along the grid of city streets.

1.1.4 Minkowski Distance

The Minkowski Distance is a weird animal. It’s a generalisation of both the Euclidean and Manhattan distances. The measure is parameterised by pp, where p=1p=1 gives the Manhattan distance and p=2p=2 is the Euclidean distance.

dist(people, method = "minkowski", p = 1)
         Jimmie   Lewis  Hollis    Jody
Lewis   4.40267                        
Hollis  3.66972 0.73295                
Jody    2.21377 2.18890 1.45595        
Timothy 4.64382 1.17632 1.32317 2.43004
dist(people, method = "minkowski", p = 2)
         Jimmie   Lewis  Hollis    Jody
Lewis   3.12564                        
Hollis  2.62299 0.52857                
Jody    1.60093 1.66535 1.25542        
Timothy 3.32986 0.84908 1.16182 1.73197

I understand that the Minkowski distance can be useful for higher dimensional data, but to be honest I’ve not yet come across a situation where I’ve needed to use it.

1.1.5 Other Metrics

There are a few other distance measures available via dist().

2 kk Means Clustering

In kk Means Clustering one must specify the number of clusters in advance. The algorithm then proceeds as follows:

  1. Randomly assign observations to each cluster.
  2. Find the centroid of each cluster.
  3. Find the distance from each point to the centroid of every cluster.
  4. Assign points to the closest cluster.
  5. Return to 2.

These steps are followed until a predefined number of iterations is reached or qthere is no further variation within the clusters.

Note that kk Means Clustering does not require the calculation of a distance matrix.

An alternative to kk Means Clustering is kk Medoids Clustering, which is implemented in pam() from the cluster package.

2.1 Example: iris

The iris data are a great candidate for kk means clustering since we know the expected number of clusters.

Based on the distribution of the data we should expect that setosa should easily resolve into a separate cluster but that versicolor and virginica might well be more tricky.

To keep ourselves honest, we’ll make sure that we have an unsupervised problem. For these data the clusters are actually worse after standardising the data, so we won’t do that!

species <- iris$Species
iris <- select(iris, -Species)
set.seed(7)
(iris.kmeans <- kmeans(iris, 3, nstart = 20))
K-means clustering with 3 clusters of sizes 38, 62, 50

Cluster means:

3       5.0060      3.4280       1.4620      0.2460

Clustering vector:
  [1] 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3
 [48] 3 3 3 2 2 1 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 1 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2
 [95] 2 2 2 2 2 2 1 2 1 1 1 1 2 1 1 1 1 1 1 2 2 1 1 1 1 2 1 2 1 2 1 1 2 2 1 1 1 1 1 2 1 1 1 1 2 1 1

[1] 23.879 39.821 15.151

[7] "size"         "iter"         "ifault"

Since the initial assignment of observations to clusters is randomised, the final result might be variable. Therefore, to ensure reproducible results it’s important to seed your RNG. Also it’s possible to execute the algorithm multiple times (using the nstart parameter), which will mitigate against unfortunate initial cluster assignment which might cause the algorithm to converge to a local optimum.

We can check the cluster assignments against the known labels.

table(species, iris.kmeans$cluster)
            
species       1  2  3
  setosa      0  0 50
  versicolor  2 48  0
  virginica  36 14  0

This confirms our suspicions: setosa was cleanly separated into a single cluster. However, the incidences of versicolor and virginica have been split between two clusters. There is a tendency for virginica to be found in cluster 1 and versicolor to be assigned to cluster 2, but this is clearly not the outcome that we were looking for. Perhaps the situation could be improved with some feature engineering?

Suppose that we didn’t know the right number of clusters in advance. How could we generate a decent guess? We could look at what fraction of the variance in the data is explained by a given clustering.

iris.kmeans$betweenss / iris.kmeans$totss
[1] 0.88428

Obviously, as the number of clusters increases, the positions of the points within the clusters will become closer to the cluster centroids, and this ratio will approach 100%

Let’s do this systematically by changing the number of clusters.

ratios = sapply(1:10, function(k) {
  with(kmeans(iris, k, nstart = 20), betweenss / totss)
})

Finally, let’s take a quick swing at kk Medoids Clustering.

library(cluster)
iris.pam <- pam(iris, 3)

3 Hierarchical Clustering

Hierarchical Clustering does not produce a single set of clusters, rather it constructs a hierarchy of clusters. It’s then possible to cut across the hierarchy to select a clustering structure with a specific level of complexity. There are two classes of hierarchical clustering algorithms:

  • Agglomerative: a bottom=up approach where initially every observation is a cluster and these clusters are progressively merged until all observations are in a single cluster;
  • Divisive: a top-down approach where all observations are initially in a single cluster, which is then recursively split until every observation is a cluster.

Both of these approaches can become computationally expensive with large data sets.

We’re going to use data from the cluster package. We’ll focus on a subset of votes.repub (percent of votes given to the Republican candidate in presidential elections) where there are no missing data.

votes.repub <- select(votes.repub, X1960:X1976)

3.1 Example: Agglomerative Clustering

Let’s cluster the voting data using an agglomerative clustering algorithm.

votes.dist <- dist(votes.repub)
(votes.hclust <- hclust(votes.dist))

Call:
hclust(d = votes.dist)

Cluster method   : complete 
Distance         : euclidean 
Number of objects: 50

This is what the results look like:

The structure of the tree does not require explanation. However, perhaps the interpretation of the Height axis does. This can loosely be interpreted as the distance between clusters. So, for example, the clusters which are merged towards the bottom of the dendrogram are close together, while those that are merged near to the top of the dendrogram are far apart.

We can extract concrete clusters from this tree (or “dendrogram”) using cutree(). Suppose that we can to divide the states into 3 clusters.

cutree(votes.hclust, k = 3)
       Alabama         Alaska        Arizona       Arkansas     California       Colorado 
             1              2              2              3              2              2 
   Connecticut       Delaware        Florida        Georgia         Hawaii          Idaho 
             2              2              3              3              3              2 
      Illinois        Indiana           Iowa         Kansas       Kentucky      Louisiana 
             2              2              2              2              2              1 
         Maine       Maryland  Massachusetts       Michigan      Minnesota    Mississippi 
             2              2              3              2              2              1 
      Missouri        Montana       Nebraska         Nevada  New Hampshire     New Jersey 
             2              2              2              2              2              2 
    New Mexico       New York North Carolina   North Dakota           Ohio       Oklahoma 
             2              2              3              2              2              2 
        Oregon   Pennsylvania   Rhode Island South Carolina   South Dakota      Tennessee 
             2              2              3              3              2              3 
         Texas           Utah        Vermont       Virginia     Washington  West Virginia 
             2              2              2              3              2              2 
     Wisconsin        Wyoming 
             2              2

We could achieve a similar effect by cutting the tree at a specified height by using the h parameter to cutree().

Another route to agglomerative clustering is via agnes().

3.2 Linkage

You may have noted above that the cluster method used was “complete”. What does this mean? When clusters are being combined we need to measure the distance between clusters so that we can identify which ones are closest together. There are various ways to do this, the most important of which are:

  • Complete Linkage: consider all pairs of points from two clusters and the distance between those clusters is taken as the distance between the pair of points which are furthest apart;
  • Single Linkage: similar to complete linkage, but the distance between clusters is determined by the points which are closest together.

Complete linkage is the default in hclust().

The choice of linkage function can, in some cases, have a big effect on the shape of clusters identified in hierarchical clustering.

Let’s cluster the voting data using single linkage.

(votes.hclust <- hclust(votes.dist, method = "single"))

Call:
hclust(d = votes.dist, method = "single")

Cluster method   : single 
Distance         : euclidean 
Number of objects: 50

This is what the results look like:

3.3 Example: Divisive Clustering

votes.diana <- diana(votes.dist)

It’s worth printing votes.diana because it captures a lot of information. It’s a little too lengthy to include here though.

We see that the resulting dendrogram is not significantly different to what we obtained with agglomerative clustering.

4 Exercises

  1. Use kk Means Clustering to group the observations in the mtcars data. Is it important to standardise these data first? Vary the number of clusters and choose an appropriate value for kk. Interpret the clusters.

  2. Use the animals data from the cluster package to perform hierarchical clustering. Try different distance measures and select the one that makes the most sense. Check ?dist to ensure that you understand how missing values are treated.

  3. Perform hierarchical clustering on the mtcars data. Plot the dendrogram. Does the structure make sense?

  4. Perform hierarchical clustering on the USArrests data. Try all possible linkage methods and see what effect they have on the results.
